{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486909"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:49:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:49:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"204"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/204"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.21,0.27,0.25,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98760"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/204"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81151"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6376"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44328"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98760"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two day history of worsening fever, chills and right flank pain. She had a urinary tract infection three months ago that was treated with trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole for five days. She has no other health issues. On examination her temperature is 37.2\u00b0C, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg and pulse 86/min. She has mild tenderness in the right flank. Bedside urine dipstick is positive for nitrites and leucocytes and the urine is sent for microscopy, culture and sensitivities (MCS). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit and renal ultrasound","Admit and give intravenous ceftriaxone","Outpatient oral amoxicillin-clavulanate and GP follow-up","Admit, and give intravenous amoxicillin, gentamicin","Outpatient oral trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute pyelonephritis, but is haemodynamically stable and afebrile. Therefore, her acute pyelonephritis can be managed on an outpatient basis. Indications for admission of patients with acute pyelonephritis include inability to tolerate oral therapy (e.g. nausea, vomiting), fever \u226538\u02daC, or sepsis/septic shock. As advised in the Therapeutic Guidelines, patients with acute pyelonephritis managed as an outpatient should be commenced on amoxicillin-clavulanate for 14 days unless they have an allergy to penicillin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOutpatient oral amoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E with GP follow-up is appropriate as she has no indications for hospital admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission and intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E (whether \u003Cstrong\u003Eceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eamoxicillin with gentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E) would be indicated if the patient had features suggesting severe infection such as temperature \u226538\u00b0C, inability to tolerate oral therapy, or signs of sepsis. None of these features are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as empiric therapy due to high rates of resistance (approximately 20% of \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E urine isolates are resistant).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommended duration of therapy is 14 days. Follow-up with a GP is important to review urine culture results and ensure the organism is sensitive to the prescribed antibiotic. While renal tract ultrasound may be considered at follow-up, it is not required as an urgent investigation in an otherwise well patient with uncomplicated pyelonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An otherwise well, afebrile patient with acute pyelonephritis can be managed on an outpatient basis."],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook 2020, Urinary infections, Australian Medicines Handbook, viewed 28 September 2020","Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines 2020a, Acute pyelonephritis in adults, Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines, viewed 28 September 2020","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Acute pyelonephritis in adults. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2025 [cited 2025 Apr 16]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81151"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"204"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81151"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-16T20:46:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-16T20:46:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"204"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98760"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious